 he shows, residents of Brazil's urban peripheries have formulated a new citizenship that is destabilizing the old. Their mobilizations have developed not primarily through struggles of labor but through those of the city--particularly illegal residence, house building, and land conflict. Yet precisely as Brazilians democratized urban space and achieved political democracy, violence, injustice, and impunity increased dramatically. Based on comparative, ethnographic, and historical research, Insurgent Citizenship reveals why the insurgent and the entrenched remain dangerously conjoined as new kinds of citizens expand democracy even as new forms of violence and exclusion erode it. Rather than view this paradox as evidence of democratic failure and urban chaos, Insurgent Citizenship argues that contradictory realizations of citizenship characterize all democracies--emerging and established. Focusing on processes of city- and citizen-making now prevalent globally, it develops new approaches for understanding the contemporary course of democratic citizenship in societies of vastly different cultures and histories.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCities and townszBrazil. 0aCitizenshipzBrazil. 0aDemocracyzBrazil. 0aLand tenurezBrazil. 0aLawxPolitical aspectszBrazil. 0aSociology, UrbanzBrazil. 0aSquatter settlementszBrazil. 0aUrban anthropologyzBrazil. 0aUrban policyzBrazil. 0aUrban poorzBrazil. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Demography.2bisacsh  aAgamben, Giorgio.  aBalibar, Etienne.  aBobbio, Norberto.  aBooks of Nobility.  aBrasília.  aBrubaker, Rogers.  aCatholic Church.  aCollor, Lindolfo.  aConrad, Robert Edgar.  aCovas, Mário.  aDean, Warren.  aDecree of Social Interest (DIS).  aDutra, President.  aEnglish Reform act (1884).  aErundina, Luiza.  aEzequiel.  aFernandes,